    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Apologies for Today</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lester G Freundlich letter says media and localities that profit from tobacco should apologize for it now, not waiting for centuries like those now apologizing for their involvement in slavery centuries ago</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Slavery's Fellow Travelers,'' by Eric Foner (Op-Ed, July 13):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Slavery's Fellow Travelers,'' by Eric Foner (Op-Ed, July 13):</p>
        <p>It's nice, I guess, that retrospective apologies are now politically correct. But it would be better and perhaps more sincere if we do not have to wait decades or centuries for apologies to be made for contemporary evils. The media and localities that profited from slavery long ago should critically examine some of the things they do now, and then apologize for profiting from evils like tobacco.</p>
        <p>LESTER G. FREUNDLICH  Stamford, Conn., July 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
